				\begin{document}$${{{{{\rm{E}}}}}}\left({{{{{\rm{RHE}}}}}}\right)={{{{{{\rm{E}}}}}}}_{{{{{{\rm{mea}}}}}}}-i\times {R}_{s}+{{{{{\rm{pH}}}}}}\times 0.059+{{{{{{{\rm{E}}}}}}}^{0}}_{{{{{{\rm{SCE}}}}}}}$$\end{document}where Emea is the recorded potential, R is the ohmic drop determined by EIS measurements, i is the current, and E0SCE is 0.242 V.

Cdl was measured by using CV method. Briefly, CV curves were recorded in a non-Faradaic range (−0.24 ~ −0.14 V vs. RHE) at 20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120 and 140 mV s−1, respectively. The Cdl values for the samples were then calculated by measuring the slope of the fitting line of currents (J) against scan rates. J was calculated according to Eq. 2:2J=Ja−Jc2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
